<HEADLINE>
<P>
TAKING UMBRAGE WITH 'GOOD MANNERS' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I would like to compliment staff writer Nikki Finke on her witty article 
regarding good manners in the '90s. 
</P>
<P>
I have a suggestion I believe covers the field most succinctly, and it has to 
do with -- of all things -- golf. 
</P>
<P>
As presently codified, the rules and etiquette of golf are far more complicated 
than any book on manners ever written; however, I would refer you to the 
ancient rules of golf. 
</P>
<P>
Play the course as you find it. Play the ball as it lies. Do what's fair. 
</P>
<P>
It seems to me that those rules cover most any social situation I have come 
across in a long life. 
</P>
<P>
DON PORTER, Los Angeles 
</P>
