<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTH BAY DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: PORT ENVIRONMENTAL DIRECTOR NAMED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Port of Los Angeles has a new director of its environmental management 
division -- Donald Rice, who has been the port's second-ranking environmental 
official for the past 10 years. 
</P>
<P>
Rice replaces Lillian Kawasaki, whom Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley appointed 
recently as manager of the city's newly created Environmental Affairs 
department. 
</P>
<P>
Rice, 45, of Huntington Beach, joined the port in 1974 as a marine 
environmental assistant and became its assistant environmental management 
director in 1980. 
</P>
<P>
During that time, he participated in dozens of scuba-dives aimed at gathering 
biological samples, planting kelp beds along the breakwater, and searching for 
historically significant shipwrecks. 
</P>
<P>
Rice's new salary will be $62,619 a year, an official with the personnel 
division said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
