<HEADLINE>
<P>
DESIGNERS GET INTO THE TRENCHES FOR SPRING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CINDY LaFAVRE YORKS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This week, department stores are filling up with the latest must-have: the 
short trench coat. 
</P>
<P>
We're not talking about utility wear. These are knee-grazing, colorful items 
with full skirts set off by snugly belted waists that have less to do with 
weather conditions than of-the-moment fashion. European designers, including 
Gianfranco Ferre for Christian Dior, Claude Montana and Martine Sitbon for 
Chloe, all show trench coats in their spring collections. As do such 
young-spirited New Yorkers as Isaac Mizrahi, Adrienne Vittadini and Marc Jacobs 
for Perry Ellis. 
</P>
<P>
Mizrahi's coats are vibrant orange. Vittadini went in for a blue plaid version. 
Marc Jacobs for Perry Ellis enlivened his belted trench with a marigold color 
tone. 
</P>
<P>
The look works well with the Los Angeles climate, says Gail Sekiguchi, fashion 
director for Nordstrom Southern California. Customers at her store are picking 
up on the short trench as an accent piece for their wardrobes, primarily 
because it is an ideal topper for cool evenings and it is light enough to be 
worn as a jacket, or even as a dress, by day. 
</P>
<P>
New York designer Donna Karan considers the DKNY short trench coat to be a 
fashion basic for spring, whether it's raining or not. 
</P>
<P>
"Donna considers it as basic as jeans for this season," her spokeswoman, Patti 
Cohen, says. Cohen has definite ideas about how to wear the new fashion item. 
</P>
<P>
"You can dress the short trench up or down. It looks good with pants or alone, 
belted over a full skirt, or unbelted over skinny pants or leggings. You can 
even wear them over bathing suits." She also points out that the length is more 
flattering than ankle-length coats on shorter women. 
</P>
<P>
Karan also added a short cotton poplin trench, shown cinched with a real 
alligator belt, to her pricier signature collection for summer. 
</P>
<P>
Some believe the look will really take off after the summer season. 
</P>
<P>
"I don't know that it is as major a look for spring as it will be later, moving 
forward into fall," says Sekiguchi, explaining that it takes time for a trend 
to catch on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Gold satin trench by Isaac Mizrahi, left, and marigold orange trench 
from Marc Jacobs for Percy Ellis are available at I. Magnin. GARY FRIEDMAN / 
Los Angeles Times; Photo, Below right, Claude Montana trench with Western-style 
belt and hidden buttons is another entry among this season's short coats. 
European and American designers alike are showing the items for this spring. ; 
Photo, Trenchant spring offerings include blue plaid version at Adrienne 
Vittadini boutique, left, double-breasted coat by Gianfranco Ferre for 
Christian Dior, and buttonless trench from Martine Sitbon for Chloe (at 
Patricia Morange). Insiders say the look will take off after summer. CHANDOHA 
VALENTINO 
</P>
