<HEADLINE>
<P>
P. M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
JAPAN POSTS $636-MILLION TRADE DEFICIT, ITS FIRST IN SIX YEARS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Japan reported a trade deficit for the first time in six years today with a 
current account shortfall for the month of January, but economists said Tokyo 
is expected to return to a trade surplus soon. 
</P>
<P>
The current account, the broadest measure of trade in goods and services, was 
$636 million in deficit after a $2.51-billion surplus a year earlier, the 
Finance Ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
Japan's last deficit, of $562 million, was recorded in January, 1984. 
</P>
<P>
Analysts said factors involved in the decrease, such as the initial depressing 
effects of a weaker yen on trade, higher oil prices and slowing auto exports, 
will continue at least for the first quarter of 1990. But they saw no cause for 
alarm. 
</P>
<P>
"The drop was largely due to seasonal factors," said Nobuyuki Saji, senior 
economist at Nikko Securities Research Centre. "It's nothing to get excited 
about." 
</P>
</TEXT>
